GitHub Actions Workflow Structure:
==================================
A GitHub Actions workflow is a YAML file that tells GitHub:
When to run → What machine to use → What steps to execute

A GitHub Actions workflow is a YAML file stored in .github/workflows/. It consists of:
name → workflow name
on → trigger event (push, pull request, schedule, manual)
jobs → groups of tasks
runs-on → runner machine (Ubuntu, Windows, macOS)
steps → sequential actions inside a job
run → execute shell commands
uses → use prebuilt GitHub Actions

The workflow automates CI/CD tasks such as building, testing, and deploying applications.


Basic Workflow Structure:
=========================
name: My Workflow

on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main

jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - name: Step 1
        run: echo "Hello"

      - name: Step 2
        run: echo "World"

1. name
Defines the workflow name shown in the GitHub Actions page.
name: My Workflow

Example:
==========
name: CI Pipeline
GitHub Actions page will display: CI Pipeline

2. on
Defines the event (trigger) that starts the workflow.

on:
  push:
Common Triggers: Run on Push

Run on Push Request: Whenever a code is pushed.
on:
  push:
Whenever code is pushed.

Run on Pull Request: Whenever a pull request is created or updated.
on:
  pull_request:

Run Manually
on:
  workflow_dispatch:

A Run Workflow button appears in GitHub.

Run on Schedule - Runs every day at midnight.
on:
  schedule:
    - cron: "0 0 * * *"

Multiple Triggers:
on:
  push:
  pull_request:
  workflow_dispatch:
  

3. jobs - A workflow contains one or more jobs.

jobs:
Think of a job as:
A group of related tasks executed on a runner.

Example:
========
jobs:
  build:
    ...

  test:
    ...

  deploy:
    ...

Workflow:
=========
Workflow
│
├── Build Job
├── Test Job
└── Deploy Job

4. Job Name - The key under jobs is the job ID.

jobs:
  build:

Here:
Job ID = build

Another example:
jobs:
  compile:
  
5. runs-on

Specifies which machine executes the job.

runs-on: ubuntu-latest

Available runners:

runs-on: ubuntu-latest
runs-on: windows-latest
runs-on: macos-latest

Visual Representation:
=====================
GitHub Repository -> GitHub Runner(Ubuntu VM) -> Execute Steps

6. steps - A job contains one or more steps.
Example:
steps:
  - name: Step 1
    run: echo "Hello"

  - name: Step 2
    run: pwd

Execution order:
================
Step 1
  ↓
Step 2

Steps run sequentially.

7. name (Inside a Step) - Provides a friendly name for the step.
- name: Print Greeting
Appears in GitHub Actions logs.

8. run - Executes a shell command.
run: echo "Hello"

Multiple commands:
------------------
run: |
  pwd
  ls -la
  echo "Done"
  
9. uses - Used to execute a prebuilt GitHub Action.

Example:
- uses: actions/checkout@v4
This action downloads your repository code onto the runner.


Complete Example:
================
name: Hello World

on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main

jobs:
  demo:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Print Greeting
        run: echo "Hello World"

      - name: Show Current Directory
        run: pwd

      - name: List Files
        run: ls -la
		

Workflow Hierarchy
Workflow
│
├── name
│
├── on
│   └── push
│
└── jobs
    │
    └── demo
        │
        ├── runs-on
        │   └── ubuntu-latest
        │
        └── steps
            │
            ├── checkout code
            ├── print greeting
            ├── pwd
            └── ls -la
			
Real DevOps Pipeline Example
name: CI Pipeline

on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main

jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Install Dependencies
        run: npm install

      - name: Run Tests
        run: npm test

      - name: Build Application
        run: npm run build

Flow: Code Push -> GitHub Actions Triggered -> Runner Created -> Checkout Code -> Install Dependencies -> Run Tests -> Build Application -> 
Job Completed
